INSERT INTO `team_members` VALUES (6,'William Fletcher','Solicitor - Director','wjf@bannerjones.co.uk','01246 861250','Clay Cross','2011-02-01 16:27:18','2012-03-22 12:16:47',1,2,0,NULL,1,4,'WilliamFletcher.jpg','image/jpeg',99773,'2011-02-07 14:54:39','William Fletcher','WilliamFletcherBubble.jpg','image/jpeg',60955,'2011-02-11 09:15:09','William Fletcher','Bristol Grammar School / Sheffield University and for professional exams Bristol Polytechnic ','1973','William has been with the firm since the 1970s and now focuses on family law and residential conveyancing. Divorce and the break-up of co-habitation relationships are the basis of his family work. It includes resolving financial arrangements, and issues surrounding children such as maintenance, residency and contact. Where necessary, he obtains injunctions to protect clients against domestic violence.\r\n\r\nOn the conveyancing side, William undertakes residential property transactions. His past experience includes civil litigation, licensing law and Wills. Since the firm enlarged in 1999, William has been Head of the Clay Cross branch office. \r\n\r\nWilliam’s long experience enables him to understand every aspect his clients’ legal problems and to give expert advice','','','Grass Cutting','Motorcycling','Alta Rica','Motorcycling Europe','Deciding my favourite drink','CQS Logo.JPG','image/pjpeg',73603,'2012-03-22 12:16:46','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',''),(8,'Anne Rogers','Solicitor ','ar@bannerjones.co.uk','01246 560 536','Glumangate','2011-02-03 12:29:32','2012-09-21 08:06:46',1,1,0,NULL,1,17,'anne roger small 2012.JPG','image/pjpeg',27439,'2012-09-19 08:41:17','Anne Rogers','AnneRogersBubble.jpg','image/jpeg',27831,'2012-09-21 08:06:45','Anne Rogers','Studied at De Montfort University, Leicester','2009','Anne originally worked for Glossops before the firm merged with Banner Jones Middleton in June 2007. Since qualifying in 2009 Anne has concentrated on Private Client work and has developed a particular interest and expertise in matters relating to the elderly client. Anne specialises in the areas of Wills, Probate, Enduring and Lasting Powers of Attorney and Court of Protection work.\r\n\r\n\r\n','','','Dancing Teacher','Walking, Yoga, Eating Out','A nice glass of white wine!','Two weeks in the Maldives','120 mile walk - Cleveland Way',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',''),(9,'Michael Parker','Litigation Executive','mp@bannerjones.co.uk','0845 263 7050','','2011-02-07 11:23:34','2011-09-27 11:45:31',1,2,0,NULL,1,34,'MichaelParker.jpg','image/jpeg',98571,'2011-03-03 14:58:39','Michael Parker','MichaelParkerBubble.jpg','image/jpeg',52808,'2011-04-04 14:47:03','Michael Parker','','','','','','Trainee Quantity Surveyor – Tarmac Roadstone\r\n','Playing Guitar\r\n','Jack Daniels\r\n','Anywhere with my family','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(11,'Rob Lowe','Accredited Police Station Representative','rl@bannerjones.co.uk','01246 560 560 ','Marsden Street','2011-02-07 11:30:02','2011-12-16 12:36:48',1,2,0,NULL,1,21,'RobLowe.jpg','image/jpeg',83694,'2011-02-07 11:30:00','Rob Lowe','RobLoweBubble.jpg','image/jpeg',45860,'2011-04-07 15:35:36','Rob Lowe','','','I joined the firm in 1998 and I’m very experienced in a wide range of general criminal work.  My main area of expertise is representing suspects detained at the police station.  I am an accredited police station representative and part of a team providing 24/7 advice and assistance at the police station.  I pride myself on being approachable, friendly and compassionate with all of my clients and I always do my very best to give sound realistic advice to achieve the best possible outcome.\r\n\r\n','','','I worked weekends at my uncles coal yard before I joined Banner Jones (then Jones and Middleton) as an office junior.','I am a follower of all things football related, especially the Spireites and Arsenal.  I also enjoy reading, walking and eating out.','Coffee in the week, something a bit stronger at weekends (unless I’m on duty at the police station of course!)\r\n\r\n','Although there’s nothing wrong with Skeggy, I do prefer it warm.  I’d have to say somewhere in the Carribean because I’ve never been.','Getting married!',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',''),(12,'Kevin Tomlinson','Solicitor - Director - Head of Criminal','kt@bannerjones.co.uk','01246 283002 ','Marsden Street','2011-02-07 11:32:22','2012-07-18 12:48:44',1,2,0,NULL,1,9,'DSC_8081Kevin.JPG','image/pjpeg',66021,'2011-03-29 11:46:56','Kevin Tomlinson','DSC_8083Kevin-updated.jpg','image/jpeg',41292,'2011-03-31 09:33:34','Kevin Tomlinson','Nottigham Trent University, Ba Law ','1985','Kevin has practised in Chesterfield since 1985, specialising in criminal defence and child care proceedings.  \r\n\r\nKevin is Ranked as one of the top 3 criminal defence lawyers in the East Midlands (Chambers Guide to the legal Profession 2009), Kevin brings a wealth of experience to our team. \r\n\r\n\r\n','','He has been a Duty Solicitor for criminal cases since the Duty scheme was introduced and is also qualified as a Solicitor Higher Courts Advocate allowing him to represent criminal defence cases in the Crown Court.\r\n\r\nKevin is a Member of the Children Panel, representing children, children’s guardians, parents and grandparents','Newspaper boy','Mountain biking. Running, music','Taylors Landlord','Being in the mountains','Viewing Mt Everest at 5800m','138_crim lit.JPG','image/jpeg',57584,'2011-11-09 16:21:31','','','136_children law.jpg','image/jpeg',40519,'2011-11-09 16:21:32','','','1_ResolutionSpecialist.jpg','image/jpeg',17384,'2011-11-09 16:26:05','',''),(13,'Bob Bashforth','Solicitor','rlb@bannerjones.co.uk','01246 283011','Marsden Street','2011-02-07 11:33:03','2012-04-10 10:44:57',1,2,0,NULL,1,20,'Bob Prof.JPG','image/pjpeg',113498,'2011-11-21 15:50:53','Bob Bashforth','bob_bubble.jpg','image/pjpeg',16100,'2011-12-22 10:17:25','Bob Bashforth','','1983','Bob who joined Banner Jones in November 2010 has specialised in Criminal Law since 1983 and has been a sole practitioner in Chesterfield for the past 12 years. \r\n\r\nBob who is Chesterfield born and bred set up his company, RL Bashforths in 1998 and has been a key provider of local Criminal Law services ever since. \r\n\r\nRobert Banner, director of Banner Jones comments “We are delighted with Bob’s decision to become part of a larger team here at Banner Jones as this will help us to move to the forefront of criminal law provision in Chesterfield. He will add a wealth of experience to the company’s already highly regarded criminal team and allow us to provide our clients with an enhanced level of service from a wider team of specialists. Bob has been involved in a number of high profile cases in recent years and we warmly welcome him to our team\r\n\r\n\r\n','','Bob is a member of the Law Society Criminal Litigation panel.','','','','','','138_crim lit.JPG','image/jpeg',57584,'2011-11-09 17:21:24','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',''),(14,'Diane Gunn','Solicitor and Mediator','dg@bannerjones.co.uk','01246 827516','Bolsover','2011-02-07 11:33:40','2012-02-02 12:04:34',1,2,0,NULL,1,25,'DianeGunn.jpg','image/jpeg',72794,'2011-02-07 11:33:39','Diane Gunn','DianeGunnBubble.jpg','image/jpeg',40428,'2011-02-11 09:18:53','Diane Gunn','Keele University, BA Law','1993','Since qualifying in 1993 Diane has been a specialist in family law. She joined the firm in 2004. Her background includes three years of working entirely on legal issues affecting children. As well as advising on contact and residency when children’s parents break-up, she can also represent children in care proceedings brought by social services agencies. Diane’s family work includes helping clients to resolve the problems of divorce and co-habitation breakups. Her experience in financial matters, including property division, enables her to give sound advice. Where necessary, Diane can obtain injunctions to prevent domestic violence.\r\n\r\nDiane’s approach is to find the best way forward for clients, helping them to reach agreement wherever possible whilst ensuring that their rights are upheld.\r\n\r\n','','Member of the Law Society Children Panel.\r\n\r\nDiane is also a Qualified Mediator with the Family Mediation Council and a member of Resolution mediation.','Paper Round','Taekwon do, reading, gardening, music, motor sport','Cup of tea','One lasting at least 12 months!','Living with 4 boys!','136_children law.jpg','image/jpeg',40519,'2011-11-09 16:29:37','','','resolution Mediator_logo.jpg','image/pjpeg',110806,'2012-02-02 12:03:50','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',''),(15,'Ruth Clarke','Legal Clerk','rmc@bannerjones.co.uk','01246 560 560 ','Marsden Street','2011-02-07 11:34:37','2011-04-01 12:55:01',1,2,0,NULL,1,26,'RuthClarke.jpg','image/jpeg',84623,'2011-02-07 12:23:03','Ruth Clarke','RuthClarkeBubble.jpg','image/jpeg',53478,'2011-02-11 09:18:59','Ruth Clarke','','','Ruth runs the Crown Court Department within the firm’s criminal law practice. Since joining in 2003, she has been involved in all cases sent to the Crown Court. She sees an important part of her role as providing care and support to firm’s clients who are facing the possibility of imprisonment. \r\n\r\nAs a legal clerk, Ruth’s responsibilities include the preparation of Crown Court files and all matters for barristers including documentation, obtaining statements and ensuring the attendance of witnesses. Ruth is also a probationary police station representative attending the police station to give advice to clients both in and out of office hours.','','','Waitress in a tea room (at 14!!)','Playing bass guitar, watching Derby County FC, Socialising','Gin & Tonic','City breaks to New York / Barcelona are my all time favourites','Starting my Police Station Accreditiation and hopefully qualifying by the end of the year!!',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(16,'Jayne Henshaw','Compliance Director','jeh@bannerjones.co.uk','01246 560543','26 Glumangate','2011-02-07 11:35:22','2012-06-27 12:29:04',1,2,0,NULL,1,14,'JayneHenshaw.jpg','image/jpeg',95302,'2011-02-07 11:35:22','Jayne Henshaw','JayneHenshawBubble.jpg','image/jpeg',54837,'2011-02-11 09:18:34','Jayne Henshaw','University of Huddersfield','1988','Jayne is our Compliance Director for Legal Practice, bringing over 20 years of experience in private practice to the role, including both private and publicly funded work. Jayne’s responsibilities cover both strategic and operational compliance, a large part of which focuses on client care.  Jayne reports to the Board of Management. \r\nFrom Chesterfield, Jayne was educated at St Helena Girls High School and then went on to the University of Huddersfield where she studied law, followed by the Law Society Finals at Chester College of Law. \r\n\r\nJayne undertook her articles, qualified in 1988 and worked for two local law firms before joining Banner Jones in 2000. \r\n','','Jayne is a member of the Derby Law Society and a member of the Law Society Risk and Compliance Service','Putting bottoms in Smartie tubes in a factory','Trying to train a labrador and Karate','Gin','Russia','Learning to speak Serbo Croat',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',''),(17,'Andrew Fielder','Solicitor - Director','arf@bannerjones.co.uk','0114 275 5266','Sheffield','2011-02-07 11:36:32','2012-09-05 08:58:45',1,2,0,NULL,1,29,'AndrewFielder.jpg','image/jpeg',100986,'2011-02-07 11:36:31','Andrew Fielder','AndrewFielderBubble.jpg','image/jpeg',39947,'2011-02-11 09:20:06','Andrew Fielder','LLB (Hons) University of Nottingham','2007','Andrew joined Banner Jones as a Trainee Solicitor in September 2005, qualifying in September 2007. Andrew undertakes a mixture of corporate and commercial property work including: company formations, commercial agreements, business sales and purchases, shareholder and partnership agreements, commercial leases, development projects and commercial premises sales and acquisitions.\r\n\r\n','','','Building site labourer','Football (both playing and supporting), golf and hiking.','Milk','Round the world trip ','Learning to do some DIY following the purchase of my house.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',''),(18,'Peter Jones','Solicitor - Director','pwej@bannerjones.co.uk','01246 283016 ','Marsden Street','2011-02-07 11:36:57','2012-07-18 12:44:23',1,2,0,NULL,1,2,'PeterJones.jpg','image/jpeg',97616,'2011-02-07 11:36:56','Peter Jones','PeterJonesBubble.jpg','image/jpeg',46331,'2011-02-11 09:17:19','Peter Jones','University of Kent','','When you contact me it will be because you are dealing with significant changes in your life and need help.  I apply detailed knowledge of the law and over 30 years of experience to support you through change.  For nearly 15 years I was the Banner Jones partner responsible for the Staveley office, which gave me a breadth of experience in legal problems.\r\n\r\nMy clients include parents and other relatives trying to make arrangements for contact with children, couples separating and needing me to deal with their finances, victims (both men and women) of domestic violence, parents and grandparents where social services have become involved with children.  I have for many years been a member of the Child Care Panel.  \r\n\r\nI am a Duty Solicitor and give urgent personal support to clients arrested or before the Magistrates. \r\n\r\nI focus on the issues that matter and advise you what your options are.  I believe in giving frank, straightforward and clear advice.  I ensure you know how the law applies to your case.  I support you to make the right choices, and put them into effect.  I am a member of Resolution and subscribe to their Code of Practice that can be found here: http://www.resolution.org.uk/.  Resolution commits family lawyers to resolving disputes in a non-confrontational way wherever possible.  I share the belief that family law disputes should be dealt with in a constructive way designed to preserve people’s dignity and to encourage agreement. \r\nFamily problems are most often based on in a lack of communication.  Negotiation, even at the door of the court, is very important in all areas of law but particularly family law.  There is not a week goes by when I am not at court personally advising my clients, representing their interests, and presenting their case.\r\n','Notable recent cases I have been involved in:\r\n\r\nRe: S (2012)\r\n\r\nI represented grandparents whose daughter’s baby was going to be taken into care.  I successfully argued that she should be cared for by my clients, and the case ended with a Special Guardianship Order being made in their favour.  \r\n\r\nRe:  M (2012)\r\n\r\nI ensured my client on divorce, had the matrimonial home transferred into her name, so that she retains the full value of the asset she brought into the marriage.\r\n \r\nRe:  W (2012)\r\n\r\nMy client was victim of significant abuse and violence from her former partner.  He denied everything.  After a full day’s court hearing the Judge agreed that all 18 of the allegations against him, including the most serious, were proven.\r\n\r\nRe:  C (2012)\r\n\r\nMy client’s baby was taken into foster care after birth.  Mother had a recent history of drug abuse and domestic violence.  I supported mother in her decision that the best interests of her daughter was adoption to a safe and secure family home as soon as possible.\r\n\r\nRe:  S (2012)\r\n\r\nMy client was a victim of domestic abuse and intimidation and manipulation by her former partner the father of her child.  I supported her and helped her to understand how she was being abused.  I directed her to the agencies that could provide her with help.  She grew in confidence and eventually with my help was able to make a complaint to the police.  Her former partner is now charged with harassment and subject to a restraining order.\r\n\r\nRe:  M (2011)\r\n\r\nMy client wanted contact with a child he had never met.  However he continued to be in trouble with the police.  I advised him what steps he needed to take before he could apply to the court for a contact order.\r\n\r\nRe:  C (2011)\r\n\r\nSocial Services alleged that my client’s toddler was at risk of harm from him and his partner and applied to take the child into care.  I successfully defended an application to remove the child and at the final hearing I argued my client’s case and the Magistrates rejected the social services’ concerns.\r\n\r\nRe:  C (2012)\r\n\r\nSocial Services alleged my client was by not able to protect his small boy.  At an interim hearing the Judge ordered that his son should be removed from his care but I arranged for assessments which resulted in him being returned to his father’s care and the family reunited.\r\n\r\nRe: C (2011)\r\n\r\nI acted for grandmother.  The her two grand-children lived with her.  Mother wanted them returned to her.  Over a long court case we answered objection after objection raised by mother to grandmother’s care of the children but eventually at a final hearing the arrangements were confirmed and an order made that the children should continue to live with their grandmother, my client.\r\n\r\nRe:  T (2011)\r\n\r\nMy clients received threatening letters from a solicitor instructed by grandmother demanding contact with their children.  I advised an approach which contained an offer of contact and a robust set of expectations from grandmother.  The grandmother solicitors’ letters were shown to be empty threats.\r\n\r\nRe:   V (2011)\r\n\r\nActing for mother in divorce proceedings I helped negotiate a mutually satisfactory agreement for the shared care of the children.\r\n\r\nRe:   H (2011)\r\n\r\nI acted for father who was accused of domestic violence towards his wife.  At the end of lengthy court proceedings Social Services accepted that mother had an alcohol problem which made the disharmony worse, and the children were placed in the primary care of their father.  We negotiated contact with mother, and also put in place a negotiated financial arrangement.\r\n\r\nRe: F (2011)\r\n\r\nFather and mother could not agree how to share the care of their young children.  On my advice mother had put forward a proposal for shared care that she considered to be in the best interests of the children.  Father alleged that the children were not safe in their mother’s care.  After a 3 day hearing the judge accepted my client’s case and rejected all father’s allegations.  The judge made an order in the terms of the proposal we had made.\r\n\r\nRe:  L (2011)\r\n\r\nDivorce proceedings were relatively straightforward but, although we made a number of offers, husband would not come to agreement on the financial matters.  At a final hearing, with evidence being given by both husband and wife, I established that husband had assets abroad that he had not properly disclosed and the full value of the matrimonial home was transferred to my client the wife.\r\n\r\nRe:  E (2011)\r\n\r\nMy client was the mother of a delightful little boy but her lifestyle caused social services to intervene claiming that she was unable to give him the care and attention that he needed.  I advised my client, and who agreed that her son lived with her parents, so she is able to continue to maintain a relationship with him and the threat of adoption was removed.\r\n\r\nRe:  S (2011)\r\n\r\nMy client, the husband, lived in the matrimonial home and although it was in his sole name had always agreed that his former wife was entitled to one half of it.  In negotiation with the wife’s solicitors an arrangement was reached which allowed him to continue to live in the property and did not affect the benefits entitlement of either husband or wife.\r\n\r\n','Member of the Criminal Litigation panel','Washing up in a restaurant on the south coast of France in 100 degree heat.  Worst job in the world. ','I sing in the Chesterfield Philharmonic Choir, of which I am the chairman.  I enjoy going out with friends and going to music festivals with my grown up children and their friends and their fathers','A light sharp hoppy bitter','In the garden of our house in Brittany, chopping up wood, pulling up weeds, cutting the lawn. I am very fortunate that I get the chance to do that often.','Arriving in time for Bestival at the Isle of Wight, and wearing a ridiculous costume throughout.','138_crim lit.JPG','image/jpeg',57584,'2011-11-09 16:34:03','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',''),(19,'Rachel Barlow','Legal Executive','rcb@bannerjones.co.uk','01246 283004','Marsden Street','2011-02-07 11:38:56','2012-07-18 12:47:10',1,2,0,NULL,1,8,'RachaelBarlow.jpg','image/jpeg',93195,'2011-02-07 11:38:56','Rachael Barlow','RachaelBarlowBubble.jpg','image/jpeg',32697,'2011-02-11 09:14:14','Rachael Barlow','','2003','Rachel specialises in advising and assisting clients with regard to all issues arising from the breakdown of their relationship, including divorce, cohabitation disputes, financial disputes, issues concerning children and domestic abuse.\r\n\r\nRachel recognises that the breakdown of a relationship is often a very stressful time for all concerned and aims to deal with matters in as sensitive a way as possible, maintaining a friendly and down to earth approach.\r\n\r\nRachel has recently been nominated and shortlisted for The National Family Law Awards 2012.  The Family Law awards were launched by Jordan Publishing to highlight the important work done by family lawyers and to celebrate their commitment, hard work and outstanding achievements.\r\n\r\n','','','Checkout operator at Morrisons.','Gym, reading, socialising, walking','Glass of Pinot Grigio, or a cup of tea.','Two weeks in the Maldives doing nothing but sunbathing and snorkelling','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'',''),(20,'Richard Barlow','Solicitor, Director','rpb@bannerjones.co.uk','01246 560530','Glumangate','2011-02-07 11:39:34','2012-07-23 13:16:00',1,1,0,NULL,1,16,'RichardBarlow.jpg','image/jpeg',80062,'2011-02-07 11:39:33','Richard Barlow','RichardBarlowBubble.jpg','image/jpeg',37165,'2012-07-23 13:15:59','Richard Barlow','','2000','I am a solicitor in the Private Client Department.  I specialise in the setting up of Wills for clients, tailored to their needs, the administration of deceased’s estates, inheritance tax planning, the completion and registration of powers of attorney and also advising the elderly regarding the preservation of assets.\r\n\r\nI recognise that for clients these are often very sensitive and difficult matters emotionally to deal with and my aim is to ensure that the process involved runs as smoothly and stress-free as possible.\r\n\r\nI qualified as a solicitor in January 2000 and since then have gained considerable and valuable experience in dealing with Private Client matters, from the more simple and straightforward through to complex and high value estates and tax planning schemes. I have dealt with the estate of a person who died without a Will and who left 99 relatives all of whom I traced and between whom I distributed the estate. I have dealt with multi-million pound value estates upon which I have successfully reduced Inheritance Tax to a minimum by applying the appropriate tax reliefs available. I have experience in dealing with all aspects of an estate including the registration of the death, arranging of the funeral and arranging that where appropriate unoccupied property is maintained, insured and secure.','','','Paper Round','Playing and watching football (but only if it\'s Sheffield United), running','A pint of Easy Rider real ale','Either 3 weeks on a deserted Maldivian island or walking in the Scottish High